article.description: Sophomore guard Lisa Etienne scored 13 points and Hartford handed Brigham Young (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) its third loss in five games, 60-43 on Saturday.
article.headline: Hartford bounces back from streak-breaker with win
article.linkText: Hartford bounces back with win over Brigham Young
article.story:
WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Brigham Young center Dani Kubik
Wright didn't miss a shot Saturday, but it meant nothing as the No.
23 Cougars lost for the third time in five games.

Wright scored 16 points on 7-for-7 shooting from the field, but
Hartford used a collapsing double-team defense to limit her to just
one basket after halftime, and won 60-43.

Lisa Etienne, Ikea Witt and Erica Beverly combined to score 37
points for the Hawks (5-3).

Shawnee Slade, who entered the game leading BYU (4-3) in scoring
at 11.4 points per game, went scoreless on 0-for-7 shooting.

"It seems like a roller coaster right now," said Wright, whose
only field goal in the second half came on a three-point play with
4:31 remaining. "We were our worst enemy. Nothing they did. Its
all what we did. We got in a funk and they started beating us."

Etienne scored five of her 13 points as Hartford (5-3) opened
the second half with a 10-0 run. Witt, who finished with 12 points,
capped the run with a layup that gave Hartford a 39-25 lead.

The Hawks, who had a 20-game home winning streak snapped
Wednesday with a 59-53 loss to Seton Hall, were playing a
nationally ranked team at the Chase Arena for the first time.

The defending America East Conference champions recorded their
first win over a ranked opponent in the 2006 NCAA Tournament when
they defeated No. 19 Temple.

"Thats the story of us so far this year, one great game, one
bad game," Hartford coach Jennifer Rizzotti said. "We have to
find a way to string a couple of good ones together. I told the
kids if were capable of doing that today, then you shouldnt ever
expect anything less of yourself."

Wright scored eight of her 12 first-half points in the final
three minutes before halftime. The Cougars, 5-for-18 from
three-point range, started working the ball to Wright in the low
post and her basket with 29 seconds left cut Hartford's lead to
29-25 at halftime.

"We started off slow, then came back in the first half," BYU
coach Jeff Judkins said. "Weve always been a better second half
team but we just couldn't seem to get it in gear. You have to give
Hartford a lot of credit for that."

Forward Erica Beverly scored half of her 12 points as Hartford
jumped out to a 13-6 lead. Beverly, who was 4-for-4 from the field,
injured her left knee with 5:43 left and did not return to the
game. Beverly will undergo an MRI examination Sunday or Monday to
determine the extent of the injury.

Witt, who became the ninth player in Hartford history to score
1,000 career points, gave the Hawks a 25-15 with 7:34 remaining in
the first half. Hartford took its biggest lead at 58-37 when Witt
scored with 4:35 left.

"This means our expectations are going to be higher for
ourselves," Witt said. "If we can come out and play like that
against BYU, I don't see why we can't come out and play like that
against everyone we play. But we still have to work hard and keep
playing our game."
